Good catch.

The right solution would be to give both statements production and operator terminals the same priority.
Something like this:
```
STMT : STMT ADDOP STMT {left, 1}
     | STMT MULOP STMT {left, 1}
     | "(" STMT ")" | NUMBER;
ADDOP : "+" {1}
      | "-" {1};
MULOP : "*" {2}
      | "/" {2};
NUMBER: /\d+(.\d+)?/;
```
But, unfortunately, that doesn't work due to ambiguity between Non-terminal and Terminal parse in the part of the grammar of the form `ADDOP: "+" {1}...`. The parser needs more than 1 lookahead to decide if this is Terminal or Non-Terminal.

Futhermore, #17 will provide less typing when you have e.g. same priority in all production of a rule. 
This will enable something like this:
```
STMT {left}: STMT ADDOP STMT {1}
           | STMT MULOP STMT {2}
STMT: "(" STMT ")" | NUMBER;
ADDOP {1}: "+" | "-";
MULOP {2}: "*" | "/";
NUMBER: /\d+(.\d+)?/;
```


I'll work on fixing this.

In the mean time, a workaround is to use directly terminal operators in STMT definitions.
```
STMT : STMT "+" STMT {left, 1}
     | STMT "-" STMT {left, 1}
     | STMT "*" STMT {left, 2}
     | STMT "/" STMT {left, 2}
     | "(" STMT ")" | NUMBER;
NUMBER: /\d+(.\d+)?/;

```

