This is definitely not related to presto db. If I'm not wrong, this about the implementation pyhive/presto. 

Let's say we have 10 users in users table.  In case of presto sqlalchemy, ( I added little print statement at presto#exexcute  ) it will call execute 10 times, once for each user.  

The query will be like 
select .... Blah blah.. where id = 1 limit 1;

select .... Blah blah.. where id = 2 limit 2;


Where as in case of MySQL sqlalchemy, the query is like

select ...... where id in (1,2,3,4,...10);

So, it's definitely implementation difference between both.

@ebozduman, we usually follow this style when submitting a new PR:
- Only one commit: so here you need to squash your two commits into one.
- "Fixes #ISSUE_ID" is usually written in the PR body and not in the title. Github will automatically add the PR_ID to the commit title. Then, if someone wants to inform himself about the whole story, he will be able to open the merged pull request and find the issue id.

